<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-755-310  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 755 310.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  July 30 1990 v219 n5 p10(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FCC takes initiatives on Computer III. (the Federal CommunicationsCommission acts to minimize damage from a court ruling thatoverturns the FCC's 1985 Computer III policy that permitted Bellregional holding companies to offer enhanced services withoutmaintaining separate subsidiaries) (New of the Week)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mason, Charles.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) issued an orderallowing Bell regional holding companies (RHCs) to continue toprovide enhanced services under approved comparably efficientinterconnection (CEI) plans.andP;  The FCC wants to minimize damagefrom a Jun 1990 court reversal of the FCC's Computer III rules.andO;In June, the US Court of Appeals in San Francisco overturned theFCC's 1985 policy that permitted the RHCs to offer enhancedservices without maintaining separate subsidiaries.andP;  The FCCbelieves it would be impractical or impossible to force the RHCsto revert to separate subsidiary status after more than threeyears of offering enhanced services on an unseparated basis.andP;  TheFCC notes that proceedings are scheduled for fall 1990 that couldre-affirm the abolition of the separate subsidiary requirement.andO;However, the FCC has placed a freeze on any new offerings pendingfurther action.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Federal Communications CommissionBell Regional Holding CompaniesTelephone companiesDeregulationGovernment RegulationSubsidiary CompaniesCommunications Service SuppliersTelecommunications.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>